@endnode


@node Requirements " Requirements "
@{b}@{" Small Magic  ()" SYSTEM "run >NIL: multiview SmallMagic.Demo"} Requirements@{ub}                    
              @{"  " LINK} Even a simple thing like  some icons have their requirements.
              @{"  " LINK} 
              @{"  " LINK} SmallMagic is in eight  colours so @{b}Kickstart 2.0+@{ub} is
              @{"  " LINK} needed in order to open a wb in at least 3 planes.
              @{"  " LINK} 
              @{"  " LINK} In order for the icons te be proportioned properly a 
              @{"  " LINK} resolution must  be used in which the pixel ratio is
              @{"  " LINK} about 1:2. Examples are:
              @{"  " LINK}            -Pal/NTSC Hires       NoLace   (Overscan)     
              @{"  " LINK}            -Pal/NTSC SuperHires  Laced    (Overscan)
              @{"  " LINK}            -Super72              NoLace
Introduction  @{"()" LINK Introduction}
Requirements  @{"()" LINK Requirements} The original MAgicWB or even better my more friendly
Installation  @{"()" LINK Installation} palette  should  be used in  order to  prevent  sore                   
Distribution  @{"()" LINK Distribution} eyes and headaches.
The  Credits  @{"()" LINK Credits}   
              @{"  " LINK} Some handy work is required in order to copy all the
              @{"  " LINK} different icons to your harddisk. 
              @{"  " LINK}      
   June 1995  @{"  " LINK}      
@endnode

@node Introduction " Introduction "
@{b}@{" Small Magic  ()" SYSTEM "run >NIL: multiview SmallMagic.Demo"} Introduction@{ub}  
              @{"  " LINK} By now I can safely presume everybody reading this is familiar                              
              @{"  " LINK} with the MagicWB series.  The 8 colour icons have spread round
              @{"  " LINK} the Amiga scene like fire and are used by allmost everyone.
              @{"  " LINK} But for  people that  do not have  expensive monitors  and who 
              @{"  " LINK} can't  stand  interlace (like  me) this archive offers a  good
              @{"  " LINK} alternative.
              @{"  " LINK}
              @{"  " LINK} Over the last months more collections  of rescaled icons  have 
              @{"  " LINK} appeared on the  scene. Obviously all of them  claim to be the 
              @{"  " LINK} best. I think I should comment  on that fact. Those icons that
              @{"  " LINK} do look better than mine (I'll admit it) are invariably bigger 
Introduction  @{"()" LINK Introduction} than my  icons and  therefore more  memory hungry.  And really
Requirements  @{"()" LINK Requirements} should we  wonder at the  fact that bigger  icons can be  more
Installation  @{"()" LINK Installation} beautifull?  I could  make the  best  icons ever  if you  only 
Distribution  @{"()" LINK Distribution} wanted three of them on your screen simultaniously. ;)
The  Credits  @{"()" LINK Credits}
              @{"  " LINK} Besides icons  this archive also  contains fonts,  dockbrushes 
              @{"  " LINK} and  backgrounds. If you  like the new drawers I  used in this 
              @{"  " LINK} archive  you should  check out  the SmallBench archive because
   June 1995  @{"  " LINK} that is where I got them from. 
@endnode

@node Installation " Installation "
@{b}@{" Small Magic  ()" SYSTEM "run >NIL: multiview SmallMagic.Demo"} Installation@{ub}  
              @{"  " LINK} Do  not copy the  icons in  this archive  directly over  the
              @{"  " LINK} original workbench icons. This way information  contained in
              @{"  " LINK} the original icons will be lost forever!
              @{"  " LINK} For  replacing the icon  images, but leaving  tooltypes  and
              @{"  " LINK} position information  intact, you can use (for  example) one
              @{"  " LINK} of the following utilities:
              @{"  " LINK}
              @{"  " LINK} - IconUpdate.lha     aminet:util/wb    
              @{"  " LINK} - MUI_IconUpd12.lha  aminet:util/wb  
              @{"  " LINK} - Iconizer           aminet:pix/icon (in Iconpack)
              @{"  " LINK}
Introduction  @{"()" LINK Introduction} Device icons (Ram, disks etc) can be  found in the diskicons
Requirements  @{"()" LINK Requirements} drawer. They are saved as drawer icons because they would be
Installation  @{"()" LINK Installation} invisible otherwise.
Distribution  @{"()" LINK Distribution}
The  Credits  @{"()" LINK Credits} Do not forget to update the system default icons that can be
              @{"  " LINK} found in envarc:sys/.
              @{"  " LINK} 
              @{"  " LINK} 
   June 1995  @{"  " LINK} 
@endnode

